Name: Phosphorus (yellow)
Classification: Pyrophoric solids - Category 1
Hazard statement: Catches fire spontaneously if exposed to air
Rationale for classification: UNRTDG No. 1381, Class: 4.2, Subsidiary risks Class: 6.1, PGI

Name: Cresol
Classification: Pyrophoric solids - Not applicable (m-cresol)           Not classified (o- and p-cresol)
Rationale for classification: Classified as "liquid"(m-cresol), according to GHS definition. Not pyrophoric when in contact with air at ordinary temperatures: the flashing points are 599degC for o-cresol (ICSC, 2000) and 559degCfor p-cresol (ICSC, 2000).

Name: Sodium decylbenzenesulfonate (C10)
Classification: Pyrophoric solids - Not classified (solid)
Rationale for classification: Considered non-pyrophoric when in contact with air at ordinary temperatures since the substance is used as laundry detergents (CERI-NITE Hazard Assessment, 2006), and sodium dodecylbenzenesulphonate (C12), an analog of sodium decylbenzenesulfonate, is classified as non-flammable (ICSC, 1999).

Name: Ammonium dodecylbenzenesulphonate (C12)
Classification: Pyrophoric solids - Classification not possible (as a solid)
Rationale for classification: No data available

Name: Carbon black
Classification: Pyrophoric solids - Not classified(Materials of animal or vegetable origin), Classification not possible(Materials of mineral origin)
Rationale for classification:
Materials of animal-and-plant origin: It is based on the UN Number 1361 (CARBON, animal or vegetable origin, Class4.2, Packing Group IIorIII).
Materials of mineral origin: No data.

Classification: Pyrophoric solids - Classification not possible (as a solid)
Rationale for classification: No data available

Name: chlorophenol
Classification: Pyrophoric solids - Not applicable (o)  Not classified (m, p)
Rationale for classification:
It is a liquid according to the definition of GHS. (o-body)
It was judged that it did not ignite spontaneously from the fact that the measurement of flash point was performed at the temperature of 112 degC or more (ICSC (1999)). (m-body, p-body)

Name: Tridecylbenzenesulphonic acid (C13)
Classification: Pyrophoric solids - Not classified (solid)
Rationale for classification: Classified into Class 8 (UN#2585 Alkyl sulfonic acids (solid) or Aryl sulfonic acids (solid) (with not more than 5% free sulfuric acid)) (UN Recommendation on the Transport of Dangerous Goods).

Name: Polychlorinated terphenyls
Classification: Pyrophoric solids - Not classified (solid)
Rationale for classification: Considered non-pyrophoric when in contact with air at ordinary temperatures since the substance had previously been used as a fire-retardant (EHC 140 (1993). Classified into Class 9 (UN#3152 (Polyhalogenated Biphenyls (solid; excluding polychlorinated biphenyls (UN#3432, solid); those with concentrations of not more than 50mg/kg are not included in the Dangerous Goods list), or Polyhalogenated Terphenyls (solid; those with concentrations of not more than 50mg/kg are not included in the Dangerous Goods list)) (UN Recommendation on the Transport of Dangerous Goods).
